{"title_page": "Kevin Porter Jr.", "text_new": "{{short description|American basketball player (b. 2000)}}\n{{Infobox basketball biography\n| name = Kevin Porter Jr.\n| image = Kevin Porter Jr. (48885562137).jpg\n| image_size = \n| caption = Porter with the Cavaliers in 2019\n| number = 4\n| position = [[Shooting guard]]\n| height_ft = 6\n| height_in = 4\n| weight_lb = 203\n| league = [[National Basketball Association|NBA]]\n| team = Cleveland Cavaliers\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|2000|5|4}}\n| birth_place = [[Seattle|Seattle, Washington]]\n| nationality = American\n| high_school = [[Rainier Beach High School|Rainier Beach]]<br>(Seattle, Washington)\n| college = [[USC Trojans men's basketball|USC]] (2018\u20132019)\n| draft_year = 2019\n| draft_round = 1\n| draft_pick = 30\n| draft_team = [[Milwaukee Bucks]]\n| career_start = 2019\n| years1 = {{nbay|2019|start}}\u2013present\n| team1 = [[Cleveland Cavaliers]]\n| highlights = \n* [[Washington Mr. Basketball]] (2018)\n| nba_profile = \n| bbr = porteke02\n}}\n\n'''Bryan Kevin Porter Jr.''' (born May 4, 2000) is an American professional [[basketball]] player for the [[Cleveland Cavaliers]] of the [[National Basketball Association]] (NBA). He played [[college basketball]] for the [[USC Trojans men's basketball|USC Trojans]]. He played high school ball at Ranier Beach and led the Vikings to the state playoffs in each of his four years.\n\n==Early life==\nPorter was born in [[Seattle|Seattle, Washington]] to Ayanna and Bryan Kevin Porter Sr.<ref name=\"bio\">{{cite web |title=Kevin Porter Jr. |url=https://usctrojans.com/roster.aspx?rp_id=8800 |publisher=University of Southern California Athletics |accessdate=December 28, 2018}}</ref> His father played [[American football|football]], basketball, and [[baseball]] at [[Rainier Beach High School]] in Seattle in the 1990s. In July 2004, when Kevin Jr. was four years old, his father was shot five times and killed while trying to help someone being attacked.<ref name=\"evans\">{{cite web |last1=Evans |first1=Jayda |title=Kevin Porter Jr. lost his father when he was 4. Now he\u2019s living up to his legacy at Rainier Beach |url=https://www.seattletimes.com/sports/high-school/kevin-porter-jr-living-up-to-his-fathers-legacy-at-rainier-beach/ |website=[[The Seattle Times]] |accessdate=December 28, 2018 |date=February 24, 2017}}</ref> As a result, he was raised by his mother, who became his role model.<ref name=\"blockus\">{{cite web |last1=Blockus |first1=Gary R. |title=Previously Unheralded Kevin Porter Jr. Looks To Show He Belongs With USA Basketball |url=https://www.usab.com/news-events/news/2018/06/mu18-porter-feature.aspx |publisher=[[USA Basketball]] |accessdate=December 28, 2018 |date=June 2, 2018}}</ref> Porter played sports to both pay homage to his late father and recover from the loss of him.<ref name=\"crawford\">{{cite web |last1=Cotterill |first1=TJ |title=Hothead? Bad attitude? No more. Kevin Porter Jr. found a father figure in Jamal Crawford to become state\u2019s best player |url=https://www.thenewstribune.com/sports/high-school/article205780354.html |website=[[The News Tribune]] |accessdate=December 28, 2018 |date=March 19, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==High school career==\nPorter convinced his mother to enroll him at Rainier Beach High School instead of [[O'Dea High School]] in Seattle, because his father had played sports there and he wanted to preserve the tradition. In his senior campaign, he averaged 27 points, 14 rebounds, and 5 assists, as Rainier Beach finished with a 22\u20137 record.<ref name=bio/> On March 3, 2018, Porter recorded 22 points and 11 rebounds in a Class 3A state championship game loss to [[Garfield High School (Seattle)|Garfield High School]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Evans |first1=Jayda |title=Brandon Roy gets second state title as Garfield works OT to beat Rainier Beach for 3A crown |url=https://www.seattletimes.com/sports/high-school/brandon-roy-gets-second-state-title-as-garfield-works-ot-to-beat-rainier-beach-for-3a-crown/ |website=[[The Seattle Times]] |accessdate=December 29, 2018 |date=March 3, 2018}}</ref> At the end of the season, he was named [[Washington Mr. Basketball]] by the state coaches association.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Cotterill |first1=TJ |title=Mr. Basketball: Who do coaches say is the top high school basketball player in the state |url=https://www.thenewstribune.com/sports/high-school/article202272464.html |website=[[The News Tribune]] |accessdate=December 29, 2018 |date=February 26, 2018}}</ref>\n\nPorter was considered a five-star [[college recruiting|recruit]] by recruiting services [[247Sports.com|247Sports]] and [[Rivals.com|Rivals]] and a four-star recruit by [[ESPN]].<ref name=espn>{{cite web |title=Kevin Porter |url=http://www.espn.com/college-sports/basketball/recruiting/player/_/id/214110/kevin-porter |publisher=[[ESPN]] |accessdate=December 29, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Kevin Porter |url=https://n.rivals.com/content/prospects/2018/kevin-porter-425 |publisher=[[Rivals.com|Rivals]] |accessdate=December 29, 2018}}</ref><ref name=247sports>{{cite web |title=Kevin Porter Jr. |url=https://247sports.com/Player/Kevin-Porter-Jr-90019/high-school-172429/ |publisher=[[247Sports.com|247Sports]] |accessdate=December 29, 2018}}</ref> He was the top-ranked player from Washington in the 2018 class and received offers from several [[NCAA Division I]] programs, including [[UCLA Bruins men's basketball|UCLA]], [[Oregon Ducks men's basketball|Oregon]], and [[Washington Huskies men's basketball|Washington]], before committing to [[USC Trojans men's basketball|USC]].<ref name=espn/><ref>{{cite web |last1=Goldberg |first1=Rob |title=4-Star SG Kevin Porter Jr. Announces Commitment to USC |url=https://bleacherreport.com/articles/2719519-4-star-sg-kevin-porter-jr-announces-commitment-to-usc |publisher=[[Bleacher Report]] |accessdate=December 29, 2018 |date=July 2, 2017}}</ref> Porter became the first USC player since [[DeMar DeRozan]] in 2008 to be rated a five-star recruit by Rivals.<ref name=bio/>\n\n{{College athlete recruit start|40=no|collapse=no|year=2018}}\n{{College athlete recruit entry\n| recruit      = Kevin Porter Jr.\n| position     = [[Shooting guard|SG]]\n| hometown     = [[Seattle|Seattle, WA]]\n| highschool   = [[Rainier Beach High School|Rainier Beach]] (WA)\n| feet         = 6\n| inches       = 4\n| weight       = 195\n| commitdate   = July 2, 2017\n| scout stars  =\n| rivals stars = 5\n| 247 stars    = 5\n| espn statrs  = 4\n| espn grade   = 89\n}}\n{{College athlete recruit end\n| 40               =\n| year             = 2018\n| rivals ref title = USC 2018 Basketball Commitments\n| scout ref title  = \n| espn ref title   = 2018 USC Trojans Recruiting Class\n| 247 ref title    = \n| rivals school    = usc\n| 247 school       = \n| espn schoolid    = 30\n| scout overall    =\n| rivals overall   = 16\n| 247 overall      = 27\n| espn overall     = 40\n| accessdate       = December 29, 2018\n| bball            = yes\n}}\n\n==College career==\nPorter debuted for USC on November 6, 2018, scoring 15 points off the bench on 6-of-7 shooting in an 83\u201362 win over [[Robert Morris Colonials men's basketball|Robert Morris]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Nov 6, 2018 - Robert Morris 62, USC 83 |url=https://basketball.realgm.com/ncaa/boxscore/2018-11-06/Robert-Morris-at-USC/310384 |publisher=[[RealGM]] |accessdate=December 29, 2018 |date=November 6, 2018}}</ref> On November 20, against [[Missouri State Bears men's basketball|Missouri State]], he suffered a quadriceps contusion. He returned on December 1 versus [[Nevada Wolf Pack men's basketball|Nevada]] but left after 4 minutes because he was hindered by the injury.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Kaufman |first1=Joey |title=USC\u2019s Kevin Porter Jr. still sidelined with thigh injury, but eyes a late December return |url=https://www.ocregister.com/2018/12/20/uscs-kevin-porter-jr-still-sidelined-with-thigh-injury-but-eyes-a-late-december-return/ |website=[[Orange County Register]] |accessdate=December 29, 2018 |date=December 20, 2018}}</ref> He missed nine games with a quad contusion, and returned again on January 10, 2019, scoring 5 points in 25 minutes.<ref>{{cite web |title=USC vs. Oregon State - Box Score |url=http://www.espn.com/mens-college-basketball/boxscore?gameId=401087126 |publisher=[[ESPN]] |accessdate=January 14, 2019 |date=January 10, 2019}}</ref> Three days later, however, he was suspended indefinitely by USC for \"personal conduct issues.\"<ref>{{cite web |last1=Bonagura |first1=Kyle |title=USC freshman Kevin Porter Jr. suspended indefinitely, coach says |url=http://www.espn.com/mens-college-basketball/story/_/id/25754912/kevin-porter-jr-usc-trojans-suspended-game-vs-oregon-ducks |publisher=[[ESPN]] |accessdate=January 14, 2019 |date=January 13, 2019}}</ref> Regardless, Porter stated that he would finish the season with the team<ref>{{cite web |last1=McCollough |first1=J. Brady |title=USC\u2019s Kevin Porter Jr. responds to his indefinite suspension from the team |url=https://www.baltimoresun.com/sports/college/basketball/mens/la-sp-usc-porter-suspension-20190114-story.html |website=[[The Baltimore Sun]] |accessdate=January 14, 2019 |date=January 14, 2019}}</ref> and then played in the last three games of the season. He averaged 9.8 points, four rebounds, and 1.4 assists in 22 minutes a game, playing in 21 of USC's 33 games.<ref name=\"theringer.com\">https://www.theringer.com/nba/2019/6/19/18684292/kevin-porter-jr-2019-nba-draft</ref>\n\nAt the conclusion of his freshman season, Porter announced his intention to forgo his remaining collegiate eligibility and declare for the [[2019 NBA draft]].\n\n==Professional career==\n===Cleveland Cavaliers (2019\u2013present)===\n[[File:Kevin Porter (48836273567) (cropped).jpg|180px|thumb|right|Porter at the grand opening of the [[Rocket Mortgage FieldHouse]] in 2019]]\nIn the [[2019 NBA draft]], Porter was selected 30th overall by the [[Milwaukee Bucks]], but was later traded to the [[Cleveland Cavaliers]] via the [[Detroit Pistons]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Detroit Pistons Acquire Tony Snell and Draft Rights to 30th Pick Kevin Porter Jr|url=https://www.nba.com/pistons/news/detroit-pistons-acquire-tony-snell-and-draft-rights-30th-pick-kevin-porter-jr|work=NBA.com|date=June 21, 2019|accessdate=June 23, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Cavs Acquire Draft Rights to Kevin Porter Jr.|url=https://www.nba.com/cavaliers/releases/porter-jr-trade-190626|work=NBA.com|date=June 27, 2019|accessdate=June 27, 2019}}</ref> On July 3, 2019, the [[Cleveland Cavaliers]] announced that they had signed Porter.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nba.com/cavaliers/releases/draft-picks-signings-190703|title=Cavaliers Sign Garland, Windler and Porter Jr.|date=July 3, 2019|website=NBA.com|accessdate=July 3, 2019}}</ref> On October 23, 2019, Porter made his debut in NBA, started in an 85\u201394 loss to the [[Orlando Magic]] with 1 rebound, two assists and a steal.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.espn.com/nba/recap?gameId=401160627|title=Magic, Vucevic beat Cavaliers in season opener|date=October 23, 2019|website=ESPN.com|accessdate=October 23, 2019}}</ref> Porter scored a career high 18 points in 31 minutes in a 123 to 105 loss to the New York Knicks. He finished the game with 18 points, 4 rebounds, 2 assists, and a steal.\n\n==Career statistics==\n{{NBA player statistics legend}}\n\n===College===\n{{NBA player statistics start}}\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| [[2018\u201319 NCAA Division I men's basketball season|2018\u201319]]\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| [[2018\u201319 USC Trojans men's basketball team|USC]]\n| 21 || 4 || 22.1 || .471 || .412 || .522 || 4.0 || 1.4 || .8 || .5 || 9.5\n{{S-end}}\n\n==Player profile==\nSince the start of the [[2018\u201319 NCAA Division I men's basketball season|2018\u201319 season]], Porter was projected as a first-round prospect for the [[2019 NBA draft]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Woo |first1=Jeremy |title=NBA Draft Watch: USC's Kevin Porter Jr. Deserves Your Attention |url=https://www.si.com/nba/2018/11/12/nba-draft-2019-prospect-usc-kevin-porter-jr-deserves-your-attention |website=[[Sports Illustrated]] |accessdate=December 29, 2018 |date=November 12, 2018}}</ref> He looks up to [[James Harden]], as both players are left-handed.<ref name=\"theringer.com\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{basketball stats|nba=kevin/porter_jr./1629645}}\n\n{{Cleveland Cavaliers current roster}}\n{{2019 NBA draft}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Porter, Kevin Jr.}}\n[[Category:2000 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:African-American basketball players]]\n[[Category:American men's basketball players]]\n[[Category:Basketball players from Washington (state)]]\n[[Category:Cleveland Cavaliers players]]\n[[Category:Milwaukee Bucks draft picks]]\n[[Category:Shooting guards]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Seattle]]\n[[Category:USC Trojans men's basketball players]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American basketball player (b. 2000)}}\n{{Infobox basketball biography\n| name = Kevin Porter Jr.\n| image = Kevin Porter Jr. (48885562137).jpg\n| image_size = \n| caption = Porter with the Cavaliers in 2019\n| number = 4\n| position = [[Shooting guard]]\n| height_ft = 6\n| height_in = 4\n| weight_lb = 203\n| league = [[National Basketball Association|NBA]]\n| team = Cleveland Cavaliers\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|2000|5|4}}\n| birth_place = [[Seattle|Seattle, Washington]]\n| nationality = American\n| high_school = [[Rainier Beach High School|Rainier Beach]]<br>(Seattle, Washington)\n| college = [[USC Trojans men's basketball|USC]] (2018\u20132019)\n| draft_year = 2019\n| draft_round = 1\n| draft_pick = 30\n| draft_team = [[Milwaukee Bucks]]\n| career_start = 2019\n| years1 = {{nbay|2019|start}}\u2013present\n| team1 = [[Cleveland Cavaliers]]\n| highlights = \n* [[Washington Mr. Basketball]] (2018)\n| nba_profile = kevinporterjr\n| bbr = porteke02\n}}\n'''Bryan Kevin Porter Jr.''' (born May 4, 2000) is an American professional [[basketball]] player for the [[Cleveland Cavaliers]] of the [[National Basketball Association]] (NBA). He played [[college basketball]] for the [[USC Trojans men's basketball|USC Trojans]]. He played high school ball at Ranier Beach and led the Vikings to the state playoffs in each of his four years.\n\n==Early life==\nPorter was born in [[Seattle|Seattle, Washington]] to Ayanna and Bryan Kevin Porter Sr.<ref name=\"bio\">{{cite web |title=Kevin Porter Jr. |url=https://usctrojans.com/roster.aspx?rp_id=8800 |publisher=University of Southern California Athletics |accessdate=December 28, 2018}}</ref> His father played [[American football|football]], basketball, and [[baseball]] at [[Rainier Beach High School]] in Seattle in the 1990s. In July 2004, when Kevin Jr. was four years old, his father was shot five times and killed while trying to help someone being attacked.<ref name=\"evans\">{{cite web |last1=Evans |first1=Jayda |title=Kevin Porter Jr. lost his father when he was 4. Now he\u2019s living up to his legacy at Rainier Beach |url=https://www.seattletimes.com/sports/high-school/kevin-porter-jr-living-up-to-his-fathers-legacy-at-rainier-beach/ |website=[[The Seattle Times]] |accessdate=December 28, 2018 |date=February 24, 2017}}</ref> As a result, he was raised by his mother, who became his role model.<ref name=\"blockus\">{{cite web |last1=Blockus |first1=Gary R. |title=Previously Unheralded Kevin Porter Jr. Looks To Show He Belongs With USA Basketball |url=https://www.usab.com/news-events/news/2018/06/mu18-porter-feature.aspx |publisher=[[USA Basketball]] |accessdate=December 28, 2018 |date=June 2, 2018}}</ref> Porter played sports to both pay homage to his late father and recover from the loss of him.<ref name=\"crawford\">{{cite web |last1=Cotterill |first1=TJ |title=Hothead? Bad attitude? No more. Kevin Porter Jr. found a father figure in Jamal Crawford to become state\u2019s best player |url=https://www.thenewstribune.com/sports/high-school/article205780354.html |website=[[The News Tribune]] |accessdate=December 28, 2018 |date=March 19, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==High school career==\nPorter convinced his mother to enroll him at Rainier Beach High School instead of [[O'Dea High School]] in Seattle, because his father had played sports there and he wanted to preserve the tradition. In his senior campaign, he averaged 27 points, 14 rebounds, and 5 assists, as Rainier Beach finished with a 22\u20137 record.<ref name=bio/> On March 3, 2018, Porter recorded 22 points and 11 rebounds in a Class 3A state championship game loss to [[Garfield High School (Seattle)|Garfield High School]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Evans |first1=Jayda |title=Brandon Roy gets second state title as Garfield works OT to beat Rainier Beach for 3A crown |url=https://www.seattletimes.com/sports/high-school/brandon-roy-gets-second-state-title-as-garfield-works-ot-to-beat-rainier-beach-for-3a-crown/ |website=[[The Seattle Times]] |accessdate=December 29, 2018 |date=March 3, 2018}}</ref> At the end of the season, he was named [[Washington Mr. Basketball]] by the state coaches association.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Cotterill |first1=TJ |title=Mr. Basketball: Who do coaches say is the top high school basketball player in the state |url=https://www.thenewstribune.com/sports/high-school/article202272464.html |website=[[The News Tribune]] |accessdate=December 29, 2018 |date=February 26, 2018}}</ref>\n\nPorter was considered a five-star [[college recruiting|recruit]] by recruiting services [[247Sports.com|247Sports]] and [[Rivals.com|Rivals]] and a four-star recruit by [[ESPN]].<ref name=espn>{{cite web |title=Kevin Porter |url=http://www.espn.com/college-sports/basketball/recruiting/player/_/id/214110/kevin-porter |publisher=[[ESPN]] |accessdate=December 29, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Kevin Porter |url=https://n.rivals.com/content/prospects/2018/kevin-porter-425 |publisher=[[Rivals.com|Rivals]] |accessdate=December 29, 2018}